blanca is THE finest restaurant in New York City. 17 course tasting menu of astonishing creativity, unlike anything you will ever experience. There are no tables at Blanca, instead there is a a long white bar with captain's chairs in full view of the open kitchen. The staff are kind, knowledgeable, and passionate about the food, and the wine list runs to rare gems you've never heard of and probably won't ever be able to find in retail markets. Eating here is a special treat, well worth the difficulty of getting a reservation.  Bonus: if you're still hungry, Roberta's take-out pizza is right next door.

Hands down my favorite restaurant in the world.  The quality of food and service grossly out weighs any other restaurant of this caliber. A constant variety of music pulls you on a journey while the always changing menu of divine food enlightens the soul. Main stay dishes come in many variables throughout the year, making a monthly visit all the more worth it.  Laughter and happiness is sure to ensue in this Brooklyn staple.

Another amazing meal at Blanca! Each course was a journey in varied flavors and textures and I loved our meal! There were a couple courses that weren't my favorite, though they were still interesting and worth a bite, but that is to be expected over 17 dishes. (Each course is maybe 2-3 bites.) The progression was logical and had a flow from appetizer-type dishes to main course type dishes to desserts. They were harmonious and well thought out. They were also beautiful to the eye.  The server and staff were all terrific. I like their lack of pretension (despite having 2 Michelin stars) and they were really interested in our having a great meal. They were friendly and able to answer any questions about a dish. The wine pairings (plus sake, cider and beer) were very well chosen to complement the courses. The attire is casual and guests who were there that night wore everything from jeans and hipster-hat to jacket and tie, but no judgments and everyone was made comfortable and welcome.  If I had one complaint, and this applies to pretty much all tasting menus, somewhere around course 13 I am completely beyond full and the last few courses (which here included the Wagyu beef) are very uncomfortable. I manage this by having a nibble of these courses and sending the rest over to my husband who has a much bigger capacity than I. But I would like a tasting menu allowing SOME guests to skip a few courses. It's not just Blanca, but pretty much every place I have done tasting menus (and that's a lot of places.) Still, other than the pain to the pocketbook, I would happily eat here regularly.

Overall, this was probably the best dining experience I've ever had.

I really enjoyed my 2.5-hour tasting course at Blanca. Having read other reviews on Yelp, I thought I might need to order a pizza at the end. Since you walk through Roberta's to get to Blanca, my bf and I eyed people's delicious-looking pizza on our way in. We checked in at where we were on the "pizza meter" throughout the night. At first we were at 100% pizza given that we were super hungry, but after the fresh dough course, he was down to 30% and we were full by the end of the dinner. They gave us ridiculously delicious smores as a treat to take home, too.  Each course is only a few bites, but they're packed with flavors and beautifully presented. To me, a great tasting menu like this requires two things: 1) inventive use of ingredients that 2) work well together aka taste is on point. Blanca achieved both of these with flying (minimalist) colors. Particular standouts to me were the garbanzo bean soup, apple with macadamia shavings that melted in the mouth, chewy and rich carbonara, nduja sausage ravioli, sunchoke cake with cardamom and chocolate for dessert, and the fresh dough. If you're asking yourself, how good can pizza dough taste? Try some when it's steaming hot. It really tastes that good.  I also much prefer this laid-back more casual environment without the pretension of some three-star Michelin restaurants like Per Se and Eleven Madison Park. It's not a place to be seen, but rather a place to focus on the food and the experience of watching people absorbed in their craft.
